<div id="review_1548120302" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1548120302" />
    <a title="Jonathan Ashworth" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/23875789-jonathan-ashworth"><img alt="Jonathan Ashworth" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1607396811p2/23875789.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1548120302?book_show_action=true">Feb 14, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jonathan Ashworth" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jonathan Ashworth" href="/user/show/23875789-jonathan-ashworth">Jonathan Ashworth</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1548120302" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8704967509875581758">This is a Message book with a capital M. How much you like the book will largely depend on how much you like the message. This is a book for those who like the positivity &amp; promises of <i>The Secret</i>, for those who love redemption &amp; hope, for those who are broken &amp; seek solace in a message of self-improvement &amp; Christianity.<br/><br/>Lyra Acajou has many skills and uses them throughout her novel. She creates tons of tension and keeps the tension high. Her characters are unpredictable, flawed, human, real, and</span>
  <span id="freeText8704967509875581758" style="display:none">This is a Message book with a capital M. How much you like the book will largely depend on how much you like the message. This is a book for those who like the positivity &amp; promises of <i>The Secret</i>, for those who love redemption &amp; hope, for those who are broken &amp; seek solace in a message of self-improvement &amp; Christianity.<br /><br />Lyra Acajou has many skills and uses them throughout her novel. She creates tons of tension and keeps the tension high. Her characters are unpredictable, flawed, human, real, and well-rounded. The dialogue is wonderful. Her sense of narrative pacing is fluid and often superb. <br /><br />In many ways the book feels like a self-help book come to life. A lot of the story is about relationships, about work, about family, the struggles of life: all these scenes help us see Lyra Acajou's Message. Lyra writes with conviction, heart, and soul: many of her scenes feel palpable; the book is full of emotional undercurrents. <br /><br />I loved the touches of magical realism: that Lloyd becomes invisible, Sage turns into a little girl, and, yes, the philosophical mouse. At times the book feels preachy, but its characters know this and comment on it: you can't say they're not self-aware! <br /><br />There's also a vintage current running through this book, reminiscent of <i>The Pilgrim's Progress</i>. Love, Hate, Resentment, and X are all characters in their own right, pushing and pulling the human characters towards or away from their destinies. <br /><br /><i>The Isolation of X</i> is full of Hope and an auspicious debut from Ms. Lyra Acajou.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8704967509875581758" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


